    <sec>
      <title>3.2 Comparison with other single- and multi-label methods</title>
      <p>In <xref rid="btw656-T5" ref-type="table">Table 5</xref> we report a comparative benchmark of different methods on the S60 dataset (<xref rid="btw656-B6" ref-type="bibr">Du <italic>et al.</italic>, 2009</xref>). For sake of comparison, results of SChloro were computed using a jackknife test, while performance scores for other methods were taken from literature (<xref rid="btw656-B26" ref-type="bibr">Wang <italic>et al.</italic>, 2015</xref>). In particular, we report overall single-label accuracies using the same annotation scheme consisting of four different labels (E = envelope, S = stroma, L = lumen, M = thylakoid membrane), respectively, for our method and for other five different single-label methods available in literature: SubChlo (<xref rid="btw656-B6" ref-type="bibr">Du <italic>et al.</italic>, 2009</xref>), ChloroRF (<xref rid="btw656-B25" ref-type="bibr">Tung <italic>et al.</italic>, 2010</xref>), SubIdent (<xref rid="btw656-B22" ref-type="bibr">Shi <italic>et al.</italic>, 2011</xref>), BS-KNN (<xref rid="btw656-B9" ref-type="bibr">Hu and Yan, 2012</xref>) and MultiP-Schlo (<xref rid="btw656-B26" ref-type="bibr">Wang <italic>et al.</italic>, 2015</xref>). The results indicate that SChloro provides in general more balanced predictions compared to others. Other methods tend to over-predict the more abundant labels in the dataset (i.e. thylakoid membrane and stroma), whereas SChloro scores, on average, better on overall accuracy and in all the remaining compartments (e.g. compare accuracy results for the lumen and envelope labels).
